# Lisa data-source credentials — copy to .env.local and fill in.
# .env.local is git-ignored. NEVER commit real values: this repo is public.
# For the scheduled GitHub Action, the same values go into
# Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions (not into any file).

# ── Shopify ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Shopify admin → Settings → Apps and sales channels → Develop apps
# → Create app "Lisa" → Configure Admin API scopes: read_products,
# read_orders → Install app → reveal Admin API access token (shpat_…)
SHOPIFY_STORE_DOMAIN=outdoorbengal.myshopify.com
SHOPIFY_ADMIN_TOKEN=shpat_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

# ── Google (one service account covers both GSC and GA4) ────────────
# console.cloud.google.com → create/select project → enable
# "Google Search Console API" and "Google Analytics Data API"
# → IAM & Admin → Service Accounts → create "lisa-sync" → Keys →
# create JSON key. Then grant the service account's email address:
#   · Search Console: property Settings → Users and permissions → Add user
#     (Restricted is enough)
#   · GA4: Admin → Property access management → Add user (Viewer)
# Point this at the downloaded key file (keep it OUTSIDE the repo or
# matching the service-account*.json ignore pattern):
GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS=/absolute/path/to/service-account-key.json

# GSC property exactly as registered (sc-domain:outdoorbengal.com for a
# domain property, or the full URL for a URL-prefix property)
GSC_SITE_URL=sc-domain:outdoorbengal.com

# GA4 numeric property id: GA Admin → Property → Property details
GA4_PROPERTY_ID=123456789

# ── Optional ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# AHREFS_API_KEY=
